        {
          "content": "# Migration Guide for Pending Features\n\nGenerated from the open pull requests reviewed for `mangowhoiscloud/claude-code`: #51, #52, and #53.\n\n## PR #51: Enhance Statsig event logging in GitHub workflows\n\n### Summary of changes based on the PR description\n\nThe PR description states that this change logs additional issue-management events, including events for issues closed as duplicates and duplicate comments, while keeping workflow logging consistent with existing patterns.\n\n### Changed-file technical summary\n\nThe files returned for this PR show a different implementation surface than the PR description: they add a Rust-porting automation workflow and supporting command/scripts.\n\nChanged files reviewed:\n\n- `.claude/commands/port-to-rust.md`\n- `.github/workflows/port-to-rust.yml`\n- `scripts/extract_rust_from_markdown.py`\n- `scripts/make_prompt.sh`\n\nThe workflow is a manually dispatched GitHub Actions workflow that clones a source repository, generates an LLM prompt from the repository contents, calls a selected LLM provider, extracts Rust code from the model output, creates a Cargo project, retries compilation fixes, opens a generated pull request, and uploads artifacts.\n\n### New configuration or environment variables mentioned\n\nWorkflow dispatch inputs:\n\n- `source_repo_url` - required Git URL for the Python or C++ repository to port.\n- `branch` - optional branch or tag, defaulting to `main`.\n- `llm_provider` - choice of `openai`, `anthropic`, or `google`, defaulting to `openai`.\n- `model` - model name, defaulting to `gpt-4o-mini`.\n\nRepository secrets and local authentication mentioned:\n\n- `OPENAI_API_KEY` - required when `llm_provider` is `openai`.\n- `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` - required when `llm_provider` is `anthropic`.\n- `GOOGLE_API_KEY` - required when `llm_provider` is `google`.\n- `GH_TOKEN` or `gh auth login` - required locally for the Claude command that triggers and watches the workflow.\n\nWorkflow environment variables include `MODEL`, `PROVIDER`, `SRC_URL`, and provider-specific API key variables during the build and retry steps.\n\n### Installation or usage instructions\n\n1. Configure the provider secret for the selected LLM provider in repository secrets.\n2. Run the workflow manually with `workflow_dispatch`, providing `source_repo_url`, `branch`, `llm_provider`, and `model` as needed.\n3. Alternatively, use the added Claude command flow in `.claude/commands/port-to-rust.md`, which triggers `.github/workflows/port-to-rust.yml` with `gh workflow run` and downloads the `port-to-rust-output` artifact.\n4. Review the generated Cargo project under the workflow artifact path `workspace/port-rust/` and the logs included in the same artifact set.\n5. Because the PR title/body and changed files do not describe the same feature area, review the PR contents before merging or communicating it as a Statsig-only change.\n\n## PR #52: feat: add shell completions (bash, zsh, fish)\n\n### Summary of changes based on the PR description\n\nThis PR adds static shell completion scripts for tab autocompletion of the `claude` command in Bash, Zsh, and Fish.\n\nChanged files reviewed:\n\n- `shell-completions/README.md`\n- `shell-completions/claude-completions.bash`\n- `shell-completions/claude-completions.zsh`\n- `shell-completions/claude-completions.fish`\n\nThe completions cover main command options, subcommands such as `config`, `mcp`, and `install`, nested subcommand options, path completions for file/directory flags, enum completions such as output format and permission mode, and model-name suggestions.\n\n### New configuration or environment variables mentioned\n\nNo new environment variables are required. Users only need to install the appropriate completion script for their shell.\n\n### Installation or usage instructions\n\n#### Bash\n\n```bash\nsudo cp shell-completions/claude-completions.bash /etc/bash_completion.d/claude\nsource /etc/bash_completion\n```\n\nFor user-only installation:\n\n```bash\nmkdir -p ~/.local/share/bash-completion/completions\ncp shell-completions/claude-completions.bash ~/.local/share/bash-completion/completions/claude\n```\n\n#### Fish\n\n```bash\nmkdir -p ~/.config/fish/completions\ncp shell-completions/claude-completions.fish ~/.config/fish/completions/claude.fish\n```\n\nFish loads completions automatically from that directory.\n\n#### Zsh\n\n```zsh\nmkdir -p ~/.local/share/zsh/site-functions\ncp shell-completions/claude-completions.zsh ~/.local/share/zsh/site-functions/_claude\n```\n\nEnsure the directory is in `fpath`, then reload completions:\n\n```zsh\nfpath=(~/.local/share/zsh/site-functions $fpath)\nautoload -U compinit && compinit\n```\n\nAfter installation, test completion with examples such as `claude <TAB>`, `claude --<TAB>`, `claude config <TAB>`, and `claude --output-format <TAB>`.\n\n## PR #53: 【Feat】Automate Docker Image Builds with GitHub Actions\n\n### Summary of changes based on the PR description\n\nThis PR adds a GitHub Actions workflow to automate Docker image builds so that a fresh image is built for updated code, improving continuous integration feedback and reducing manual build effort.\n\nChanged files reviewed:\n\n- `.github/workflows/docker-publish.yml`\n\nThe workflow builds Docker images with Docker Buildx, extracts Docker metadata, logs into the configured registry outside pull request builds, builds and pushes images outside pull requests, and signs published image digests outside pull requests.\n\n### New configuration or environment variables mentioned\n\nWorkflow-level environment variables:\n\n- `REGISTRY=ghcr.io`\n- `IMAGE_NAME=${{ github.repository }}`\n\nWorkflow and step variables/secrets:\n\n- `secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN` is used to log into the registry.\n- `TAGS` and `DIGEST` are used when signing the published image.\n\nWorkflow permissions include `contents: read`, `packages: write`, and `id-token: write`.\n\n### Installation or usage instructions\n\n1. Ensure the repository contains a valid Docker build context at `.devcontainer`, because the workflow builds with `context: .devcontainer`.\n2. Confirm that GitHub Packages permissions are acceptable for publishing to `ghcr.io/${{ github.repository }}`.\n3. The workflow runs on:\n   - A daily schedule using cron `42 13 * * *`.\n   - Pushes to `main`.\n   - Tags matching `v*.*.*`.\n   - Pull requests targeting `main`.\n4. Pull request builds do not push or sign images; non-PR builds log in, push, and sign the resulting image digest.\n5. To test, push a commit or open/update a pull request targeting `main`, then review the GitHub Actions run for the Docker workflow.\n",
          "path": "docs/MIGRATION_GUIDE.md"
        },
        {
          "content": "# Issue Analysis Report\n\nGenerated from 14 closed issues returned for `mangowhoiscloud/claude-code`.\n\n## Closed Issues by Category\n\nPrimary category is based on the first label returned for each issue. Issues may still have additional labels that are reflected in the label lists.\n\n### `bug` - 10 issues\n\n- **#50**: [BUG] Cross-project hook inheritance executes sibling project hooks inappropriately (`bug`, `has repro`, `platform:macos`, `area:tools`)\n- **#48**: Claude Code executes wrong project hooks in multi-project workspace (`bug`, `has repro`, `platform:macos`, `area:tools`)\n- **#37**: Invalid JSON Encoding in API Request Body (`bug`, `duplicate`, `area:core`, `platform:macos`, `area:api`)\n- **#32**: Calling MCP tool create-spec-doc freezes in Cursor AI + GPT-5 (`bug`, `area:mcp`, `area:ide`, `external`)\n- **#25**: Missing Tool Result Block for Tool Use ID toolu_01GUUUdR6TqtrqKTprMSuLqc (`bug`, `duplicate`, `area:core`, `platform:macos`, `area:api`)\n- **#22**: [BUG] Search/Grep tool is BROKEN (`bug`, `has repro`, `area:tools`)\n- **#21**: Invalid JSON Encoding Error During API Request (`bug`, `duplicate`, `area:core`, `platform:macos`, `area:api`)\n- **#15**: [BUG] Hard to trace changes in releases (`bug`)\n- **#13**: Agent Command Autocomplete Regression in v72 (`bug`, `has repro`, `platform:macos`, `area:tui`)\n- **#12**: [BUG] PowerLevel10k terminal theme causes Claude Code timeout and parsing failures due to ANSI escape sequence contamination (`bug`, `has repro`, `area:core`, `platform:macos`, `area:tui`)\n\n### `documentation` - 3 issues\n\n- **#39**: [DOCS] Slash command frontmatter table is misformatted (`documentation`)\n- **#30**: [Docs] Undocumented `statusline` configuration feature (`documentation`, `area:tui`)\n- **#23**: [Documentation] Claude Code release notes for v1.0.71 is not informative. Need more detailed notes. (`documentation`, `enhancement`)\n\n### `enhancement` - 1 issue\n\n- **#27**: Task color proposal - orange/ginger instead of blue. (`enhancement`, `area:tui`)\n\n## Resolution Patterns\n\n### 1. Project/tool scope isolation problems\n\nIssues **#50** and **#48** both describe cross-project hook execution in multi-project workspaces. In both reports, a Node/npm hook ran inside a Python FastAPI project without `package.json`, causing repeated `ENOENT` errors after Edit operations. Issue **#22** also points to tool reliability, reporting that Search/Grep failed to find symbols that existed in the repository.\n\n### 2. API request and conversation-state integrity problems\n\nIssues **#37** and **#21** both report invalid JSON request bodies involving missing low-surrogate handling. Issue **#25** reports a missing `tool_result` block after a `tool_use` block. These issues share a request/context integrity theme and were all marked `duplicate`.\n\n### 3. Terminal and TUI regressions\n\nIssue **#12** reports PowerLevel10k ANSI escape sequence contamination causing timeouts, parsing failures, shell integration failures, malformed requests, and hanging operations. Issue **#13** reports an agent autocomplete regression in v72. Issue **#27** requests a TUI task-color change, and issue **#30** asks for documentation of a `statusLine` TUI customization feature.\n\n### 4. Documentation and release visibility gaps\n\nIssues **#39**, **#30**, and **#23** are explicitly documentation-labeled. Issue **#15** is labeled `bug` but describes difficulty tracing what changed in releases and asks for clearer GitHub changelog and CLI version output details. Together, these show recurring need for clearer feature, release, and formatting documentation.\n\n### 5. MCP and IDE integration failures\n\nIssue **#32** reports the MCP tool `create-spec-doc` freezing in Cursor AI + GPT-5 and carries both `area:mcp` and `area:ide` labels, indicating integration sensitivity at the MCP/IDE boundary.\n\n### Cross-project impact and memory/request-context references\n\n- Cross-project impact: **#50** and **#48** explicitly involve hooks from sibling or wrong projects running in a Python project.\n- No returned issue carried an explicit `memory` label. The closest memory/request-context integrity references are **#37** and **#21**, where invalid JSON was reported at large request-body character offsets, and **#25**, where a `tool_use` ID lacked an immediately following `tool_result` block.\n\n## Platform Impact Analysis\n\n### Platform label counts\n\n| Platform label | Count | Issues |\n| --- | ---: | --- |\n| `platform:macos` | 7 | #50, #48, #37, #25, #21, #13, #12 |\n| No platform label | 7 | #39, #32, #30, #27, #23, #22, #15 |\n\nNo returned closed issue was labeled for Linux, Windows, or another platform.\n\n### Platform observations\n\n- macOS-labeled issues represent **7 of 14** closed issues.\n- macOS-labeled impact spans tool hooks (**#50**, **#48**), API/request handling (**#37**, **#25**, **#21**), TUI/autocomplete (**#13**), and terminal parsing/shell integration (**#12**).\n- Several issues without platform labels still describe environment-sensitive behavior. For example, **#15** mentions macOS 14.5 in the body but has no platform label, and **#32** is labeled by MCP/IDE area rather than by OS platform.\n\n## Area Impact Analysis\n\n| Area label | Count | Issues |\n| --- | ---: | --- |\n| `area:core` | 4 | #37, #25, #21, #12 |\n| `area:tui` | 4 | #30, #27, #13, #12 |\n| `area:tools` | 3 | #50, #48, #22 |\n| `area:api` | 3 | #37, #25, #21 |\n| `area:mcp` | 1 | #32 |\n| `area:ide` | 1 | #32 |\n\nCore and TUI were the most common labeled areas, each appearing on 4 issues. Tools and API followed with 3 issues each.\n",
          "path": "reports/ISSUE_ANALYSIS.md"
        },
        {
          "content": "# Pull Request Integration Strategy\n\nGenerated from the open pull requests reviewed for `mangowhoiscloud/claude-code`: #51, #52, and #53.\n\n## Open PRs Overview\n\n### PR #51: Enhance Statsig event logging in GitHub workflows\n\n- PR description: logs additional issue-management events, including duplicate closures and duplicate comments, while keeping workflow logging consistent.\n- Changed files reviewed: `.claude/commands/port-to-rust.md`, `.github/workflows/port-to-rust.yml`, `scripts/extract_rust_from_markdown.py`, and `scripts/make_prompt.sh`.\n- Technical summary from changed files: adds a manually dispatched workflow that ports Python/C++ repositories to Rust using OpenAI, Anthropic, or Google models. The workflow clones a source repository, generates a prompt, calls an LLM provider, extracts Rust code, creates and compiles a Cargo project, retries fixes up to three attempts, creates a PR containing the generated Rust port, and uploads artifacts.\n- Integration note: the PR description and changed files describe different feature areas. Treat this as a high-risk review item before merge.\n\n### PR #52: feat: add shell completions (bash, zsh, fish)\n\n- Changed files reviewed: `shell-completions/README.md`, `shell-completions/claude-completions.bash`, `shell-completions/claude-completions.fish`, and `shell-completions/claude-completions.zsh`.\n- Technical summary: adds static shell completion scripts for Bash, Fish, and Zsh. The scripts cover global CLI options, subcommands including `config`, `mcp`, and `install`, nested options, path completions, enum completions, and model suggestions.\n- User impact: improves discoverability and tab-completion ergonomics without changing runtime code paths.\n\n### PR #53: 【Feat】Automate Docker Image Builds with GitHub Actions\n\n- Changed file reviewed: `.github/workflows/docker-publish.yml`.\n- Technical summary: adds a Docker workflow using Buildx, Docker metadata extraction, GitHub Container Registry login, image build/push, GitHub Actions cache, and cosign signing outside pull request builds.\n- Trigger behavior: runs on a daily cron schedule, pushes to `main`, semantic version tags matching `v*.*.*`, and pull requests targeting `main`.\n- Publishing behavior: pull request builds do not push or sign images; non-PR builds publish to `ghcr.io/${{ github.repository }}` and sign the digest.\n\n## Dependencies and Conflicts\n\n### Direct file conflicts\n\nNo direct file-path conflicts were found among the reviewed PRs:\n\n- #51 adds `.github/workflows/port-to-rust.yml`, `.claude/commands/port-to-rust.md`, and helper scripts.\n- #52 adds files under `shell-completions/`.\n- #53 adds `.github/workflows/docker-publish.yml`.\n\n### Workflow-level interactions\n\n- PRs **#51** and **#53** both add GitHub Actions workflows. They do not overwrite the same workflow file, but they both increase automation surface area and required workflow governance.\n- PR **#51** uses external model-provider APIs and requires one of `OPENAI_API_KEY`, `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`, or `GOOGLE_API_KEY` depending on the selected provider. It can also create pull requests from workflow output.\n- PR **#53** requires package publishing permissions and uses `id-token: write` for signing outside pull requests.\n- PR **#53** builds from `.devcontainer`; integration should verify that this build context exists and produces the intended image.\n\n### Product-surface interactions\n\n- PR **#52** touches CLI user ergonomics. It should be validated against CLI option drift and recent autocomplete/TUI reports such as **#13**.\n- PR **#51** adds a Claude command that instructs local `gh` usage and a workflow that creates generated PRs. It should be validated against cross-project command-scope concerns raised in **#50** and **#48**.\n- PR **#51** constructs large LLM request payloads. Closed issues **#37** and **#21** show prior invalid JSON request-body failures, so payload construction and escaping should be tested carefully.\n\n## Recommended Merge Order\n\n1. **Merge PR #52 first: shell completions**\n   - Lowest integration risk because it adds static files under `shell-completions/` and does not introduce new workflow execution, secrets, publishing, or external API calls.\n   - Directly improves CLI discoverability and should be checked against the autocomplete regression described in **#13**.\n\n2. **Merge PR #53 second: Docker image workflow**\n   - Adds CI/publishing automation but is isolated to `.github/workflows/docker-publish.yml`.\n   - Validate `.devcontainer` as the Docker build context, GitHub Packages publishing, and signing behavior before enabling release expectations.\n   - This should improve build visibility, which is related to release traceability concerns in **#15**.\n\n3. **Merge PR #51 last: Rust-porting workflow / described Statsig logging**\n   - Highest risk because the PR description does not match the changed files returned for review.\n   - Adds external LLM provider calls, provider secrets, generated PR creation, helper scripts, local `gh` command instructions, and artifact upload behavior.\n   - Validate request payload escaping against the JSON/request failures in **#37** and **#21**, and validate tool/result state expectations in light of **#25**.\n\n## Risk Assessment\n\n| Risk | Affected PRs | Related closed issues | Assessment | Mitigation |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| PR description does not match changed files | #51 | #15, #23 | High: the PR may be reviewed or announced as Statsig duplicate logging while actually adding Rust-porting automation. | Require manual review of changed files and update the PR title/body before merge. |\n| Large generated LLM request payloads may hit JSON/request encoding edge cases | #51 | #37, #21 | High: the workflow builds JSON request bodies from repository contents and prior issues show invalid JSON request-body failures. | Test with repositories containing Unicode edge cases and validate generated JSON with `jq` before API calls. |\n| Tool/result state and generated automation can fail mid-run | #51 | #25, #32 | Medium-high: workflow retries builds, calls external APIs, and creates PRs; closed issues show state/integration failures around tools and MCP/IDE usage. | Add dry-run tests, clear failure logs, and artifact retention for unsuccessful runs. |\n| Cross-project command or workflow scope confusion | #51 | #50, #48 | Medium-high: the Claude command triggers a workflow on a branch/ref and operates on external source repositories. | Keep branch/ref explicit, validate `source_repo_url`, and document the execution scope before dispatch. |\n| Workflow publishing and signing permissions | #53 | #15 | Medium: publishing to GHCR and signing digests increases release/build surface area. | Verify `packages: write`, `id-token: write`, registry naming, and non-PR-only publishing behavior in a staging run. |\n| CLI completion drift | #52 | #13, #30 | Medium: static completions can become stale when CLI options or features change. | Add a maintenance checklist to update completions alongside CLI option changes. |\n| Terminal and shell compatibility | #52 | #12, #13 | Medium: shell-specific completions should be tested with Bash, Fish, Zsh, and terminal themes. | Smoke-test completions in supported shells and document known limitations. |\n| Documentation gaps for new user-facing workflows | #51, #52, #53 | #39, #30, #23, #15 | Medium: closed issues repeatedly request clearer documentation and release notes. | Require docs updates and release-note entries with each merge. |\n",
          "path": "reports/PR_INTEGRATION_PLAN.md"
        }
      ],
